From cou.: 4 HZO films were deposited on a Si substrate coated with a TiN electrode using thermal ALD at a wafer temperature of 280 °C. Hf[N(C2H5)CH3]4, Zr[N(C2H5)CH3]4, and ozone were used as the Hf precursor, Zr precursor, and oxygen source, respectively. 50 nm-thick TiN films were deposited onto the thermally oxidized Si substrate and used as the bottom electrode. HZO films with various Hf/(Hf + Zr) ratios were prepared by controlling the ALD cycle ratios of HfO2 and ZrO2, with almost identical growth rates of HfO2 and ZrO2 (∼0.12 nm per cycle on the TiN electrode). For scanning electron microscopy (SEM) analysis, the HZO films were annealed without the TiN capping electrode (post-deposition-annealing: PDA). However, it was confirmed that the presence of TiN capping layers during annealing did not significantly alter the grain size distribution.
From Soup: 4 HZO films were deposited on a Si substrate coated with a TiN electrode using thermal ALD at a wafer temperature of 280 °C. Hf[N(C 2 H 5 )CH 3 ] 4 , Zr[N(C 2 H 5 )CH 3 ] 4 , and ozone were used as the Hf precursor, Zr precursor, and oxygen source, respectively. 50 nm-thick TiN films were deposited onto the thermally oxidized Si substrate and used as the bottom electrode. HZO films with various Hf/(Hf + Zr) ratios were prepared by controlling the ALD cycle ratios of HfO 2 and ZrO 2 , with almost identical growth rates of HfO 2 and ZrO 2 (∼0.12 nm per cycle on the TiN electrode). For scanning electron microscopy (SEM) analysis, the HZO films were annealed without the TiN capping electrode (post-deposition-annealing: PDA). However, it was confirmed that the presence of TiN capping layers during annealing did not significantly alter the grain size distribution.
 ###### 
From cou.: 5 For electrical characterization, Pt (60 nm)/TiN (20 nm) top electrodes were deposited using a shadow mask and RF magnetron sputtering. After the top electrode deposition, post metallization annealing (PMA) was performed at 500 °C under a N2 atmosphere for 30 s using a rapid thermal annealing process. The composition and thickness of HZO films were examined using X-ray fluorescence spectroscopy (Quant'X, Thermo Scientific) and ellipsometry (L-116d, Gaertner), respectively. Since the film thickness of HZO films could not be directly measured on the TiN bottom electrode, the linear relationship between the areal atomic density and film thickness of HZO films on the Pt electrode and the Si substrate was first verified. From the linear relationship, the thickness of HZO films could be estimated from the layer density measured using XRF. It was confirmed that the thickness estimated from the layer density is consistent with the thickness from cross-sectional transmission electron microscopy (TEM) images in our previous studies.19,34,35,52 Polarization–voltage and capacitance–voltage characteristics were measured using a ferroelectric tester (TF analyzer 2000, Aixacct Systems) and an impedance analyser (4194A, HP) at a frequency of 1 and 10 kHz, respectively. The AC voltage amplitude used for capacitance–voltage characterization was 50 mV. The microstructure of the films was analysed using field emission SEM (SU70, Hitachi, or S4800, Hitachi). For crystal structural analysis, a grazing incidence X-ray diffraction (GIXRD) analysis was conducted using an X-ray diffractometer (X'Pert Pro, Panalytical) equipped with a Cu Kα X-ray source. For GIXRD measurements, the incidence angle was fixed at 0.5°, and a 2θ scan was conducted. A grain size distribution analysis was conducted using the watershed method implemented in the Gwyddion software.
From Soup: 5 For electrical characterization, Pt (60 nm)/TiN (20 nm) top electrodes were deposited using a shadow mask and RF magnetron sputtering. After the top electrode deposition, post metallization annealing (PMA) was performed at 500 °C under a N 2 atmosphere for 30 s using a rapid thermal annealing process. The composition and thickness of HZO films were examined using X-ray fluorescence spectroscopy (Quant'X, Thermo Scientific) and ellipsometry (L-116d, Gaertner), respectively. Since the film thickness of HZO films could not be directly measured on the TiN bottom electrode, the linear relationship between the areal atomic density and film thickness of HZO films on the Pt electrode and the Si substrate was first verified. From the linear relationship, the thickness of HZO films could be estimated from the layer density measured using XRF. It was confirmed that the thickness estimated from the layer density is consistent with the thickness from cross-sectional transmission electron microscopy (TEM) images in our previous studies. 19,34,35,52 Polarization–voltage and capacitance–voltage characteristics were measured using a ferroelectric tester (TF analyzer 2000, Aixacct Systems) and an impedance analyser (4194A, HP) at a frequency of 1 and 10 kHz, respectively. The AC voltage amplitude used for capacitance–voltage characterization was 50 mV. The microstructure of the films was analysed using field emission SEM (SU70, Hitachi, or S4800, Hitachi). For crystal structural analysis, a grazing incidence X-ray diffraction (GIXRD) analysis was conducted using an X-ray diffractometer (X'Pert Pro, Panalytical) equipped with a Cu Kα X-ray source. For GIXRD measurements, the incidence angle was fixed at 0.5°, and a 2 θ scan was conducted. A grain size distribution analysis was conducted using the watershed method implemented in the Gwyddion software.
