From cou.: 6 In this section the model proposed in ref. 42 will be briefly reviewed. As previously mentioned, Materlik et al.42 suggested that the stabilization of the metastable ferroelectric phase can be understood based on the surface energy effect. According to their model, the free energy of each phase in grains can be calculated based on the bulk free energy, surface energy, lateral dimensions of grains, and film thickness. From experiments columnar grains that span the whole film thickness are expected in doped HfO2 thin films.7 For the sake of convenience, cylindrical-shaped grains with identical size were assumed. Then, the free energy of a grain with lateral radius r and film thickness t was calculated using eqn (1):where Ggrain, Gbulk, γif and γgb are the free energy per unit volume of the grain, the free energy per unit volume of the bulk, the interface energy (the metal/oxide interface in the metal–HfO2–metal capacitor structure) and the grain boundary energy, respectively. These parameters are dependent on the film composition, and can be calculated from values reported for HfO2, Hf0.5Zr0.5O2, and ZrO2 based on Vegard's law. In ref. 42 the γif and γgb values were assumed to be identical to the surface energy, which could be problematic. This hypothesis arises from the calculation based on the nanoscale crystallites, sandwiched between the top and bottom electrodes rather than the grains in polycrystalline films. Hence, reasonable assumptions for the interface energy and grain boundary energy are required to calculate the free energy of crystalline phases in polycrystalline thin films. This will be discussed in more detail in sections 3 and 4.
From Soup: 6 In this section the model proposed in ref. 42 will be briefly reviewed. As previously mentioned, Materlik et al. 42 suggested that the stabilization of the metastable ferroelectric phase can be understood based on the surface energy effect. According to their model, the free energy of each phase in grains can be calculated based on the bulk free energy, surface energy, lateral dimensions of grains, and film thickness. From experiments columnar grains that span the whole film thickness are expected in doped HfO 2 thin films. 7 For the sake of convenience, cylindrical-shaped grains with identical size were assumed. Then, the free energy of a grain with lateral radius r and film thickness t was calculated using eqn (1) : where G grain , G bulk , γ if and γ gb are the free energy per unit volume of the grain, the free energy per unit volume of the bulk, the interface energy (the metal/oxide interface in the metal–HfO 2 –metal capacitor structure) and the grain boundary energy, respectively. These parameters are dependent on the film composition, and can be calculated from values reported for HfO 2 , Hf 0.5 Zr 0.5 O 2 , and ZrO 2 based on Vegard's law. In ref. 42 the γ if and γ gb values were assumed to be identical to the surface energy, which could be problematic. This hypothesis arises from the calculation based on the nanoscale crystallites, sandwiched between the top and bottom electrodes rather than the grains in polycrystalline films. Hence, reasonable assumptions for the interface energy and grain boundary energy are required to calculate the free energy of crystalline phases in polycrystalline thin films. This will be discussed in more detail in sections 3 and 4.
 ###### 
From cou.: 7 From eqn (1), the total free energies of each phase for a specific size of the grains can be easily calculated under the given hypothesis. According to ref. 42, Gbulk of the m-phase was the lowest whereas that of the t-phase was the highest. In the case of the surface energy (γs), the values of the t-phase were the lowest whereas the m-phase showed the highest values. The Gbulk and γs of the o-phase are in between those of the m- and t-phases. Therefore, the stable phase changes from the m-phase in the bulk to the t-phase when the grain size is decreased, but the o-phase can be stabilized within a certain range of grain size during the transition between the m- and t-phases. Accordingly, the critical grain radius (rcrit,x−y) where the total free energy of x- and y-phases is equivalent (x and y can be the t-, o-, or m-phases) can be calculated using eqn (2).
From Soup: 7 From eqn (1) , the total free energies of each phase for a specific size of the grains can be easily calculated under the given hypothesis. According to ref. 42 , G bulk of the m-phase was the lowest whereas that of the t-phase was the highest. In the case of the surface energy ( γ s ), the values of the t-phase were the lowest whereas the m-phase showed the highest values. The G bulk and γ s of the o-phase are in between those of the m- and t-phases. Therefore, the stable phase changes from the m-phase in the bulk to the t-phase when the grain size is decreased, but the o-phase can be stabilized within a certain range of grain size during the transition between the m- and t-phases. Accordingly, the critical grain radius ( r crit, x − y ) where the total free energy of x - and y -phases is equivalent ( x and y can be the t-, o-, or m-phases) can be calculated using eqn (2) .
